WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.770 --> 00:00:05.740
Let's say I had the reaction
where I had some copper ions.

00:00:05.740 --> 00:00:09.560
They have a positive
charge of 2.

00:00:09.560 --> 00:00:12.000
It's an aqueous solution.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.780
There could be some
other negative

00:00:13.780 --> 00:00:14.970
ions in that solution.

00:00:14.970 --> 00:00:16.600
Actually we could talk about
that in a little bit.

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:19.820
But we know that when you have
these ions in solution, they

00:00:19.820 --> 00:00:20.890
all disassociate.

00:00:20.890 --> 00:00:22.910
So you just have to know you
have a bunch of ions just

00:00:22.910 --> 00:00:23.780
floating around in water.

00:00:23.780 --> 00:00:26.140
There could be some other
negative ones to neutralize

00:00:26.140 --> 00:00:28.580
the entire solution, but let's
just worry about the positive

00:00:28.580 --> 00:00:29.650
ones for now.

00:00:29.650 --> 00:00:37.940
And in that solution, I'm going
to put a bar of zinc.

00:00:37.940 --> 00:00:41.465
And what happens is that they
essentially switch places.

00:00:44.510 --> 00:00:48.260
The copper wants to jump out
of your aqueous solution.

00:00:48.260 --> 00:00:50.250
I should probably draw this.

00:00:50.250 --> 00:00:53.340
Let me draw it.

00:00:53.340 --> 00:00:56.500
This is my solution.

00:00:56.500 --> 00:01:02.460
And in my solution, we make it
blue, because it's aqueous, so

00:01:02.460 --> 00:01:04.010
most of it is water.

00:01:04.010 --> 00:01:08.275
I have some copper molecules
here in the solution.

00:01:08.275 --> 00:01:11.830
They're a plus-2 charge.

00:01:11.830 --> 00:01:15.490
I could have some other ions
that are negative, like some

00:01:15.490 --> 00:01:17.790
nitrate ions or whatever, but
they're all disassociated.

00:01:17.790 --> 00:01:20.490
They're all mixing around with
the water molecules that are

00:01:20.490 --> 00:01:23.940
polar, and that's why ions
disassociate, or salts in

00:01:23.940 --> 00:01:26.460
general, disassociate
well in water.

00:01:26.460 --> 00:01:28.360
And I stick a bar
of zinc in it.

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:32.500
Solid zinc. So let me do that.

00:01:32.500 --> 00:01:35.640
So I stick of bar of
solid zinc into it.

00:01:35.640 --> 00:01:41.050
And so what this reaction says
is that these copper ions, if

00:01:41.050 --> 00:01:46.930
they can get a hold of some
electrons and essentially

00:01:46.930 --> 00:01:51.080
become neutral, they would
rather go back

00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:52.630
into the solid state.

00:01:52.630 --> 00:01:56.920
And the molecules of zinc out
here that are in the solid

00:01:56.920 --> 00:02:00.650
state, if they can lose some
electrons, they want to jump

00:02:00.650 --> 00:02:01.350
into the solution.

00:02:01.350 --> 00:02:03.210
So let me write down
the whole reaction.

00:02:03.210 --> 00:02:08.130
So if the copper can get some
electrons, they're going to go

00:02:08.130 --> 00:02:10.229
into the solid state.

00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:11.980
Copper will go into
the solid state.

00:02:11.980 --> 00:02:16.320
And if the zinc can lose some
electrons, they'll become

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:18.740
positive ions or cations.

00:02:18.740 --> 00:02:23.630
And then they will go into the
solution, plus-- I'll do the

00:02:23.630 --> 00:02:30.550
same color-- zinc plus
2 plus aqueous.

00:02:30.550 --> 00:02:33.260
Actually just so, a little
side note here, these are

00:02:33.260 --> 00:02:34.170
actual ions.

00:02:34.170 --> 00:02:35.850
We've been dealing with
oxidation numbers.

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:39.070
And when you want to know the
oxidation number of an ion,

00:02:39.070 --> 00:02:41.860
the oxidation number is the
same thing as its charge,

00:02:41.860 --> 00:02:43.780
because it's no longer
hypothetical.

00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:46.980
Remember oxidation numbers were
hypothetical charges if a

00:02:46.980 --> 00:02:47.910
bond were ionic.

00:02:47.910 --> 00:02:51.420
In this case they are ionic, so
the oxidation state, or the

00:02:51.420 --> 00:02:53.730
oxidation number is the
same as the charge.

00:02:53.730 --> 00:02:57.380
And just as a side note, the
convention, if it's written 2

00:02:57.380 --> 00:02:59.690
plus, this means that this
is a real charge.

00:02:59.690 --> 00:03:02.810
If it's written plus 2-- at
least this is the way I

00:03:02.810 --> 00:03:04.410
learned, and maybe there's
different conventions in

00:03:04.410 --> 00:03:06.980
different places-- then it would
be an oxidation state,

00:03:06.980 --> 00:03:09.300
which says, oh, it's not
necessarily an ion, but this

00:03:09.300 --> 00:03:11.380
is what it would be
if it was an ion.

00:03:11.380 --> 00:03:16.185
So if someone writes plus 2,
this is oxidation state.

00:03:16.185 --> 00:03:17.900
If they write 2 plus,
they say, hey

00:03:17.900 --> 00:03:19.400
this is a real charge.

00:03:19.400 --> 00:03:22.690
And likewise, if you just have
a regular ion that has, like,

00:03:22.690 --> 00:03:27.720
a charge of 1-- so let's say you
have Na plus-- this means

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:28.830
that it's an actual charge.

00:03:28.830 --> 00:03:30.730
If you wanted to write its
oxidation state, you would

00:03:30.730 --> 00:03:32.270
write plus 1.

00:03:32.270 --> 00:03:34.870
Small little note, it doesn't
probably make a big difference

00:03:34.870 --> 00:03:36.560
in the whole scheme of things,
but sometimes it can get

00:03:36.560 --> 00:03:39.690
confusing whether something is
an oxidation state or an ion.

00:03:39.690 --> 00:03:42.820
But depending on where you're
going to school and what your

00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:45.090
teachers or conventions are, you
might want to clarify that

00:03:45.090 --> 00:03:47.425
and just make sure that they use
the same conventions that

00:03:47.425 --> 00:03:50.290
at least I remember when
I first learned it.

00:03:50.290 --> 00:03:52.390
So anyway, let's go back
to this reaction

00:03:52.390 --> 00:03:53.470
that's happening here.

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:57.010
So let's do the half
reactions for this.

00:03:57.010 --> 00:03:59.230
So we start here, and actually
we can just look at the

00:03:59.230 --> 00:04:00.750
oxidation states
to begin with.

00:04:00.750 --> 00:04:01.720
This guy has an oxidation.

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:05.890
He has a charge of 2, which is
also an oxidation number of 2.

00:04:05.890 --> 00:04:07.990
And he goes to a
neutral charge.

00:04:07.990 --> 00:04:12.760
So clearly, he gains two
electrons, which means that he

00:04:12.760 --> 00:04:13.830
was reduced.

00:04:13.830 --> 00:04:16.450
He went from a positive
charge to a zero

00:04:16.450 --> 00:04:18.170
oxidation state or charge.

00:04:18.170 --> 00:04:19.699
So his charge was reduced.

00:04:19.699 --> 00:04:21.760
Just let me write that.

00:04:21.760 --> 00:04:23.830
So this guy was reduced.

00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:27.220
And let me write his
half reaction.

00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:30.950
He essentially started off
with some copper in the

00:04:30.950 --> 00:04:36.370
aqueous state, and he
got two electrons.

00:04:36.370 --> 00:04:37.870
That's how you get reduced.

00:04:37.870 --> 00:04:40.440
So plus two electrons.

00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:45.035
And he ended up in the solid
state of copper.

00:04:45.035 --> 00:04:48.120
And his oxidation
number is now 0.

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:52.930
Now let's see what happened to
the zinc. The zinc, it starts

00:04:52.930 --> 00:04:55.150
completely neutral in
the solid state.

00:04:55.150 --> 00:05:00.440
No extra electrons or deficiency
of electrons.

00:05:00.440 --> 00:05:05.100
But then once the zinc jumps
into the solution

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:07.000
here, he has a charge.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:08.960
So he must have lost
electrons.

00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:13.060
So the half reaction for zinc--
in this situation you

00:05:13.060 --> 00:05:19.610
have zinc as a solid and he
reacts to produce two

00:05:19.610 --> 00:05:28.830
electrons and he's in the water
and he's now an ion.

00:05:28.830 --> 00:05:30.450
So let me put that there.

00:05:30.450 --> 00:05:32.120
An aqueous solution.

00:05:32.120 --> 00:05:36.140
So if we did this experiment
right here-- and I will tell

00:05:36.140 --> 00:05:38.160
you right now this reaction
moves forward.

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:39.670
This is truly a reaction.

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:42.560
We're going to talk about, in
a second, how badly do the

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:46.240
electrons essentially want to
jump from-- where are they

00:05:46.240 --> 00:05:46.820
jumping from?

00:05:46.820 --> 00:05:51.860
They're jumping from the
zinc to the copper.

00:05:51.860 --> 00:05:54.240
So we're going to talk a little
bit about how strongly

00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:55.880
they want to jump
in the voltage.

00:05:55.880 --> 00:05:59.840
And voltage is really just how
badly does charge want to move

00:05:59.840 --> 00:06:03.020
or how much potential energy
does charge have. But this

00:06:03.020 --> 00:06:04.620
whole reaction, you just have
to think about what's

00:06:04.620 --> 00:06:07.820
happening, is that you have
charge moving from-- as the

00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:11.330
zinc jumps into the water, as
the zinc jumps into the

00:06:11.330 --> 00:06:15.070
aqueous solution, it's passing
on some charge to the copper

00:06:15.070 --> 00:06:17.330
that jumps into the
solid form.

00:06:17.330 --> 00:06:21.270
So electrons are moving here.

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:23.770
And if somehow we could
harness these moving

00:06:23.770 --> 00:06:25.390
electrons, we could
create a current.

00:06:25.390 --> 00:06:26.920
In this situation, it's
all chemical.

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:29.270
The electrons are moving around,
but they're not doing

00:06:29.270 --> 00:06:30.640
it in any organized way.

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:32.270
Because the solution
is all mixed up.

00:06:32.270 --> 00:06:34.160
But this is an interesting
situation we're

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:34.960
dealing with here.

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:38.100
And we can even talk about how
badly the electrons want to

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:40.080
move in these directions.

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:41.470
You can look at these
half reactions.

00:06:41.470 --> 00:06:44.320
You can look it up in a table,
and you can get these energies

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:46.740
or the voltage is for
these reactions.

00:06:46.740 --> 00:06:51.720
And this half reaction right
here has a voltage.

00:06:51.720 --> 00:06:52.970
So they'll sometimes right E.

00:06:52.970 --> 00:06:55.720
Sometimes it's an E not right
over there, but that's like

00:06:55.720 --> 00:06:57.800
kind of out of the scope
of at least a

00:06:57.800 --> 00:06:59.150
first-year chemistry course.

00:06:59.150 --> 00:07:02.760
But they'll say it's
0.34 volts.

00:07:02.760 --> 00:07:07.450
And then this reaction in this
direction has a potential

00:07:07.450 --> 00:07:08.770
difference.

00:07:08.770 --> 00:07:11.840
The energy is 0.76 volts.

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:14.290
If I wrote this in the other
way, if I wrote this reaction

00:07:14.290 --> 00:07:19.090
of zinc plus 2 electrons going
to zinc solid, then you would

00:07:19.090 --> 00:07:20.480
just switch the sign.

00:07:20.480 --> 00:07:25.010
But what this says is that this
state, this state right

00:07:25.010 --> 00:07:28.020
here, is a higher energy
than that state.

00:07:28.020 --> 00:07:29.830
So it wants to go in
that direction.

00:07:29.830 --> 00:07:34.510
And it wants to do that with
an energy per coulomb.

00:07:34.510 --> 00:07:36.450
And you can watch the
physics playlist on

00:07:36.450 --> 00:07:38.160
more details of volts.

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:40.720
But volt units are joules
per coulomb.

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:43.710
This is how badly the electrons

00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:46.160
want to join the copper.

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:47.520
That's the best way
of viewing it.

00:07:47.520 --> 00:07:51.090
And this is a measure of how
badly the electrons want to

00:07:51.090 --> 00:07:54.030
leave the zinc. So if you wanted
to talk about this

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:58.370
whole reaction, so this whole
reaction that we have up here,

00:07:58.370 --> 00:08:02.510
we could say it's an energy, so
the energy of this entire

00:08:02.510 --> 00:08:04.510
reaction up here.

00:08:04.510 --> 00:08:08.530
We know that electrons really
want to join the copper with

00:08:08.530 --> 00:08:11.330
this energy, and they really
want to leave the zinc with

00:08:11.330 --> 00:08:12.250
this energy.

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:15.600
So the energy of this entire
reaction, how badly do

00:08:15.600 --> 00:08:20.010
electrons want to move from zinc
to copper to form this

00:08:20.010 --> 00:08:22.340
over there, is just the
sum of the two.

00:08:22.340 --> 00:08:25.970
So you get what's 1.1 volts.

00:08:25.970 --> 00:08:28.530
You're probably saying, hey Sal,
all this talk of volts,

00:08:28.530 --> 00:08:30.190
this is interesting
and current.

00:08:30.190 --> 00:08:34.539
Is there some way that we could
construct a battery or a

00:08:34.539 --> 00:08:35.679
galvanic cell?

00:08:35.679 --> 00:08:38.179
If you don't know what a
galvanic cell is, it's what

00:08:38.179 --> 00:08:39.669
we're about to construct
right now.

00:08:39.669 --> 00:08:42.039
And the answer is obviously yes,
because that's the whole

00:08:42.039 --> 00:08:43.220
point of this video.

00:08:43.220 --> 00:08:46.080
So how can we somehow
harness that charge?

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:50.370
So let's separate the
two reactions.

00:08:50.370 --> 00:08:52.830
Let's separate the two.

00:08:52.830 --> 00:09:01.310
So let me put my
zinc bar here.

00:09:01.310 --> 00:09:04.590
I'll try to stay true to the
colors that I used earlier.

00:09:04.590 --> 00:09:08.570
And let me put my copper
bar there.

00:09:08.570 --> 00:09:11.400
Actually maybe I should
copy and paste

00:09:11.400 --> 00:09:12.720
what I wrote up here.

00:09:12.720 --> 00:09:16.640
Just so we remember the
reaction itself.

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:18.880
Actually, yeah let me do that.

