they want to grab those

00:11:37.170 --> 00:11:41.830
electrons is 0.34 volts.

00:11:41.830 --> 00:11:45.940
These guys want to jump here
and grab electrons from

00:11:45.940 --> 00:11:49.260
someplace with plus
0.34 volts.

00:11:49.260 --> 00:11:52.350
These guys want to jump off
of the bar and leave their

00:11:52.350 --> 00:11:59.350
electrons behind with
0.76 volts.

00:11:59.350 --> 00:12:00.820
So what do you think's going
to happen if we have a

00:12:00.820 --> 00:12:02.500
conducting wire here?

00:12:02.500 --> 00:12:05.960
Well those electrons are, once
this zinc just jumps off,

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:10.260
those electrons are going to
travel through the wire.

00:12:10.260 --> 00:12:13.050
And then they're going to be
available, because these are

00:12:13.050 --> 00:12:17.290
surplus electrons, to merge with
these copper ions that

00:12:17.290 --> 00:12:19.670
want to jump back
on to the bar.

00:12:19.670 --> 00:12:22.850
So these copper ions are going
to jump back on to the bar.

00:12:22.850 --> 00:12:24.780
But from this reaction
what's happening?

00:12:24.780 --> 00:12:27.380
You're having a current flow.

00:12:27.380 --> 00:12:28.750
Current is actually flowing.

00:12:28.750 --> 00:12:30.610
And what is the voltage
across this?

00:12:30.610 --> 00:12:34.450
How badly does an electron want
to go from the zinc on

00:12:34.450 --> 00:12:37.420
this bar to over here, join
with some copper in the

00:12:37.420 --> 00:12:40.400
solution and let that copper
join on to that bar?

00:12:40.400 --> 00:12:44.960
It wants to do it with
plus 1.1 volts.

00:12:44.960 --> 00:12:47.520
Now the question is the
electrons are flowing in that

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:51.480
way, what is the cathode
and what is the anode?

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:59.660
So the cathode is the positive
terminal of, well, you can

00:12:59.660 --> 00:13:02.430
already imagine, this is a
battery of sorts, right?

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:05.270
Because we are able to generate
a current by having a

00:13:05.270 --> 00:13:07.430
voltage difference across
two terminals.

00:13:07.430 --> 00:13:11.550
The cathode is the positive
terminal.

00:13:11.550 --> 00:13:14.460
That's where the electrons
want to go to.

00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:19.450
And then the anode-- and you can
familiarize yourself with,

00:13:19.450 --> 00:13:24.570
you know, just a cation is a
positive ion and anion is a

00:13:24.570 --> 00:13:26.010
negative ion.

00:13:26.010 --> 00:13:29.430
So the anode is a negative
terminal.

00:13:29.430 --> 00:13:30.890
So what's the negative
terminal here?

00:13:30.890 --> 00:13:33.800
The negative terminal is where
the electrons come from.

00:13:33.800 --> 00:13:36.560
See, electrons are coming from
the zinc jumping off.

00:13:36.560 --> 00:13:38.980
So is your negative terminal.

00:13:38.980 --> 00:13:40.140
And what's the positive
terminal?

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:41.790
That's where the electrons
want to go to.

00:13:41.790 --> 00:13:46.200
They want to go down here and be
available for these coppers

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:47.700
that want to jump out
of the solution.

00:13:47.700 --> 00:13:53.200
So this is our positive
terminal, or our cathode.

00:13:53.200 --> 00:13:54.510
This is the cathode.

00:13:54.510 --> 00:13:56.650
This is the anode.

00:13:56.650 --> 00:13:59.460
And if someone says, hey, does
oxidation or reduction occur

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:00.690
at the cathode or the anode?

00:14:00.690 --> 00:14:02.220
Well what's occurring
right here?

00:14:02.220 --> 00:14:07.620
We have zinc in its solid
state right here.

00:14:07.620 --> 00:14:11.170
We have solid zinc jumping in--
and it's neutral-- and it

00:14:11.170 --> 00:14:14.180
jumps into the solution and it
leaves two electrons behind.

00:14:14.180 --> 00:14:16.100
So it's losing electrons.

00:14:16.100 --> 00:14:19.750
When you lose electrons
you're being oxidized.

00:14:19.750 --> 00:14:23.140
So this is where the oxidation
is occurring.

00:14:23.140 --> 00:14:26.090
Likewise, on this side you
have copper ions that are

00:14:26.090 --> 00:14:30.090
already in the solution, and
they're gaining electrons.

00:14:30.090 --> 00:14:32.250
So their charge is
being reduced.

00:14:32.250 --> 00:14:36.280
So the cathode is where
reduction is taking place.

00:14:36.280 --> 00:14:38.690
Reduction.

00:14:38.690 --> 00:14:40.860
Now you're probably saying, oh
Sal, this is a nice cute

00:14:40.860 --> 00:14:45.190
little, you know, battery-- or
this is called a galvanic

00:14:45.190 --> 00:14:47.630
cell-- that, you know, you've
created this current.

00:14:47.630 --> 00:14:48.860
But I see a problem here.

00:14:48.860 --> 00:14:51.780
Because as this happens, you're
going to have more and

00:14:51.780 --> 00:14:56.670
more positive zinc ions jump
into the solution here.

00:14:56.670 --> 00:14:59.960
You have more and more positive
zinc ions in here as

00:14:59.960 --> 00:15:02.270
this progresses.

00:15:02.270 --> 00:15:07.940
And you're going to have fewer
and fewer copper ions in here.

00:15:07.940 --> 00:15:10.720
So if you assume that there
were some other, let's say

00:15:10.720 --> 00:15:17.560
there was, I mean, maybe to keep
the solution neutral--

00:15:17.560 --> 00:15:20.460
the copper is positive-- maybe
you had some chloride in

00:15:20.460 --> 00:15:28.190
there, chloride anions
that were keeping

00:15:28.190 --> 00:15:29.250
this solution neutral.

00:15:29.250 --> 00:15:31.450
And maybe you had some chlorine
anions here that were

00:15:31.450 --> 00:15:34.910
keeping, well, it started
negative but then it maybe

00:15:34.910 --> 00:15:37.150
gets a little bit more neutral
as the zinc jumps in.

00:15:37.150 --> 00:15:39.060
But once this happens a
lot then it becomes

00:15:39.060 --> 00:15:40.160
very positive, right?

00:15:40.160 --> 00:15:41.960
This is becoming more and more
positive as more and

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:43.170
more zinc jumps in.

00:15:43.170 --> 00:15:45.780
And this is becoming more and
more negative as more copper

00:15:45.780 --> 00:15:47.020
jumps on to this bar.

00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:50.340
So what can we do to
solve that problem?

00:15:50.340 --> 00:15:52.710
What they do is-- and this is
just one way to solve the

00:15:52.710 --> 00:15:54.770
problem, there's actually many
but this probably what you

00:15:54.770 --> 00:15:57.020
might encounter in your
first-year chemistry class--

00:15:57.020 --> 00:16:01.185
is they create something
called a salt bridge.

00:16:01.185 --> 00:16:03.620
And what they do is they create
a, I guess we could

00:16:03.620 --> 00:16:07.280
call it a pseudo-aqueous
solution of salt.

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:11.980
Maybe it's potassium chloride.

00:16:11.980 --> 00:16:15.320
So in here we have potassium.

00:16:15.320 --> 00:16:17.370
Potassium has a plus charge.

00:16:17.370 --> 00:16:20.600
It's aqueous, plus
chlorine with a

00:16:20.600 --> 00:16:22.300
negative charge aqueous.

00:16:22.300 --> 00:16:25.330
And I say pseudo-aqueous
because it's not really

00:16:25.330 --> 00:16:26.490
super-liquid water.

00:16:26.490 --> 00:16:28.280
What they do is they try to
make it more viscous so it

00:16:28.280 --> 00:16:29.580
just doesn't mix completely.

00:16:29.580 --> 00:16:32.190
If this was pure water, then all
of it would just fall into

00:16:32.190 --> 00:16:34.800
the solution, and you would
really have nothing up here.

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:37.150
It would be a useless device.

00:16:37.150 --> 00:16:40.460
But what they do is they create
a gel that's still

00:16:40.460 --> 00:16:43.210
aqueous enough that the
ions can move around.

00:16:43.210 --> 00:16:46.780
The sodium and chloride
ions can move around.

00:16:46.780 --> 00:16:50.520
So let's say that those are
the-- sorry, not the sodium,

00:16:50.520 --> 00:16:52.565
the potassium-- let's say
that's the potassium.

00:16:52.565 --> 00:16:56.195
And let's say the chlorine ions
are-- I already did it in

00:16:56.195 --> 00:16:58.870
that blue-- so chlorine
are the minus.

00:16:58.870 --> 00:17:02.910
And what happens is as we have
this oxidation reduction

00:17:02.910 --> 00:17:06.160
reaction that's causing these
electrons to travel from the

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:08.880
anode to the cathode, this
becomes positives, this

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:10.089
becomes negative.

00:17:10.089 --> 00:17:13.740
The salt bridge allows the
negative components of the

00:17:13.740 --> 00:17:17.240
ionized salt and just waste the
chlorine to go into the

00:17:17.240 --> 00:17:18.589
solution to neutralize it.

00:17:18.589 --> 00:17:21.220
So they'll end up having more
and more chlorine as

00:17:21.220 --> 00:17:24.130
the zinc pops off.

00:17:24.130 --> 00:17:26.020
If you were to evaporate the
solution you'd end up with a

00:17:26.020 --> 00:17:27.500
bunch of zinc chloride.

00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:32.040
And on this side, to keep the
balance here, you'll have a

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:36.610
lot of the positive parts,
components, of the salt.

00:17:36.610 --> 00:17:40.450
So the sodium would jump in to
replace the copper that's

00:17:40.450 --> 00:17:41.610
jumping out.

00:17:41.610 --> 00:17:43.810
So when you have this whole
thing it enables the current

00:17:43.810 --> 00:17:47.150
to keep flowing without having
a bad effect on the charge.

00:17:47.150 --> 00:17:48.490
Because, you know, what
happens if this

00:17:48.490 --> 00:17:50.140
becomes really positive?

00:17:50.140 --> 00:17:52.350
If this becomes really
positive-- I'll do it in

00:17:52.350 --> 00:17:56.310
vibrant color because there's no
salt bridge-- at some point

00:17:56.310 --> 00:17:58.650
the electrons are going to say,
hey, I can either go over

00:17:58.650 --> 00:18:01.120
here and drive this reaction
or, hey, I got a lot of

00:18:01.120 --> 00:18:02.860
positive stuff hanging
out here.

00:18:02.860 --> 00:18:04.430
Maybe I don't want
to leave it all.

00:18:04.430 --> 00:18:07.290
So you have to do something to
neutralize the charge here.

00:18:07.290 --> 00:18:10.310
Likewise, if this becomes really
negative from all the

00:18:10.310 --> 00:18:13.780
chlorine atoms jumping out,
electrons aren't going to want

00:18:13.780 --> 00:18:14.390
to go here.

00:18:14.390 --> 00:18:16.940
Because like charges
repel each other.

00:18:16.940 --> 00:18:19.670
So that's what having the salt
bridge neutralizing the

00:18:19.670 --> 00:18:20.650
solution does for you.

00:18:20.650 --> 00:18:22.600
It keeps it from getting
negative, and then our

00:18:22.600 --> 00:18:25.500
galvanic cell can
keep operating.

